Intelligent-FIR - Installation Guide (Single File)

Prerequisites
- Python 3.12+
- Git
- Optional (for PDF via pdfkit): wkhtmltopdf on your system PATH

1) Clone the repository
  git clone https://github.com/<your-org-or-user>/Intelligent-FIR.git
  cd Intelligent-FIR

2) Create a virtual environment
  Windows (PowerShell):
    py -3.12 -m venv .venv
    . .\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1

  macOS/Linux:
    python3.12 -m venv .venv || python3 -m venv .venv
    source .venv/bin/activate

3) Upgrade pip and install dependencies
  python -m pip install --upgrade pip
  python -m pip install -r requirements.txt

4) Optional: Enable AI features (OpenAI)
  Set OPENAI_API_KEY only if you need AI features.
  Windows (PowerShell):
    $env:OPENAI_API_KEY="sk-..."

  macOS/Linux:
    export OPENAI_API_KEY="sk-..."

5) Optional: PDF support via pdfkit
  Install wkhtmltopdf from https://wkhtmltopdf.org/downloads.html and ensure it's on PATH.
  If not installed, the app can use reportlab-based generation paths where available.

6) Run the application
  python main.py
  Open http://localhost:5000 in your browser.

Notes
- Database: SQLite is used by default and auto-created at first run.
- Templates live in frontend/src/templates, static files in frontend/static.
- If you see TemplateNotFound errors, ensure the working directory is the project root.
- If OpenAI key is not set, AI endpoints return graceful fallback messages; the app still runs.
- For PDFs, if pdfkit errors occur, install wkhtmltopdf or switch to reportlab paths.

Troubleshooting
- Upgrade pip using the interpreter inside the venv:
  python -m pip install --upgrade pip

- Reinstall dependencies:
  pip install -r requirements.txt --upgrade --force-reinstall

- Common Windows execution policy issue (PowerShell):
  If activation fails, run PowerShell as Administrator and set:
    Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope CurrentUser RemoteSigned


